The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, April 20, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, April 19: The Foreign Investment Promotion Board is believed to have cleared Zee Telefilms plan of raising $100 million as foreign currency convertible bonds subject to the condition that the company brings down the total foreign shareholding to 26 per cent by July 31 this year. However, ZTLs proposal of transferring all rights of Zee news channels and news and current affairs slots across all alpha channels to 100 per cent Indian-owned group firm, Zee Sports, is being examined by the ministry of information and broadcasting. 																								 New Delhi, April 19: Tata Motors today said it would go for an issue of foreign currency convertible bonds (FCCBs) worth $400 million. The FCCBs could be either in one or more tranches, the company informed the Bombay Stock Exchange today.																								 Mumbai, April 19: The foreign and Indian lenders of Dabhol Power Co would meet in Singapore next Monday to find a solution to the vexed issue. Majority stakeholders in the company, GE and Bechtel, have offered to sell their equity for close to $400 million.																								 Mumbai, April 19: Grasim Industries Ltd has restarted its viscose staple fibre plant at Harihar, while the pulp plant would start functioning from Wednesday following release of water from the Bhadra dam at the Tungabhadra river.																								 Sydney, April 19: The State Bank of India will open its first branch in Australia this week.
